<br>
So, one silly decision by a three-judge panel is not the end of the world, whether you agree with the decision or not, especially since it will probably get reversed when the entire Ninth Circuit rehears the case en banc, which it likely will given the uproar.  (En banc means that instead of three judges, a much larger panel of the court of appeals, usually 11 to 13 judges I think, will hear arguments and decide the case).  If not there is always the Supreme Court.<br>
<br>
Just as an aside, the majority opinion in the decision was authored by a Nixon appointee to the federal bench -- far from an evil flaming liberal &quot;faggot&quot; who would destroy the country if he had his way.  Heck, unlike most people on this board, the guy was alive BEFORE &quot;under God&quot; was added to the pledge in 1954, so just maybe he has a different perspective.  Oh well.  Perhaps if some civility was reintroduced into public discourse in America rather than all the talk-show type bull crap you see and hear all the time now, we could learn to have healthy debates and to respect others and their differences of opinion or philosophy or ideology, and thereby become an even stronger country than we are now.<br>
<br>
Just the thoughts of a politically moderate Midwesterner by birth, and Californian by transplant.<br>
